Problem 4. 
The most common way to build a local area network nowadays is an Ethernet:  basically, a single 
wire  to  which  we  can  attach  any  number  of  computers.  The  communication  protocol  is  quite 
simple:  anyone who wants to talk to another computer broadcasts a message on the wire, hoping 
the other computer will hear it. The problem is that if more than one computer broadcasts at once, 
a collision occurs  that garbles all messages we are  trying  to send.  The  transmission only works  if 
exactly one machine broadcasts at one time. 
Let’s consider a simple example.  There are n machines connected by an ethernet, and each wants 
to broadcast a message.  We can imagine time divided into a sequence of intervals, each of which 
is long enough for one message broadcast. 
Suppose each computer ﬂips an independent coin, and decides to broadcast with probability p. 

